    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-11-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-11-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="590"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d590">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 641.326/10</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MEV1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morgan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1061</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rio de Janeiro</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-11-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 21, 1917</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received January 2, 1918.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to previous correspondence and
                    especially to Embassy’s despatch No. 961, of July 13 last,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d590fn2">Not printed; enclosure printed, <hi rend="italic"
                        >ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_310">p. 310</ref>.</note> I have the honor to
                    enclose a copy of a note which the British Minister addressed to the Brazilian
                    Foreign Office on October 31 last,<note n="1" xml:id="d590fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> in which it is stated that the British Government does not
                    find it possible to relax the restrictions on the importation of coffee (from
                    Brazil), of which material there are already large stocks in the United
                    Kingdom.</p>
                <p>The British Minister also informed the Government of Brazil that imports into the
                    United Kingdom would be strictly confined to articles of prime necessity.</p>
                <p>It would therefore appear that, for the present at least, Brazil will not be able
                    to send coffee to the United Kingdom and that negotiations in that sense must be
                    suspended.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MEV1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Edwin V. Morgan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
